  },
  "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2",
  "@type": [
    "dcat:Catalog",
    "hosc:ConformanceCatalog"
  ],
  "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS — conformance catalog (the gate)",
  "dcterms:description": "Every required row is proven by RE-RUNNING its witness against an external authority; the gate (tools/gate.mjs) joins the witness results to this catalog and emits an EARL report. Fail-closed: a build with any required row unwitnessed cannot ship. Reuses W3C/community vocabulary (DCAT 3 · EARL 1.0 · schema.org) unchanged; only the hosc: namespace is minted (usr/share/ns/conformance.jsonld). This document is itself valid JSON-LD.",
  "dcterms:isDefinedBy": "https://hologram.os/ns/conformance",
  "conforms": [
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#fhs-graph",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The Linux FHS root is one self-verifying, AI-navigable semantic graph",
      "hosc:authority": "Linux Foundation FHS 3.0 · W3C JSON-LD 1.1 · W3C SHACL · schema.org + DCAT 3 + PROV-O · W3C DID Core · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/fhs-graph-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Filesystem & linked data"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#boot",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Hologram OS boots serverless in a real browser via the κ-route serving layer",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C Service Workers · WHATWG Fetch · W3C WebAssembly · cross-origin isolation (COOP/COEP)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/boot-os2-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#apps-self-contained",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Every holospace app is self-contained (0 fallbacks) in the one OS frame",
      "hosc:authority": "UOR content-addressing — identity is content not location (Law L1), verify by re-derivation (Law L5) · the holospace closure",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/audit-apps.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Holospaces"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#substrate-anchored",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The WHOLE Hologram OS and every app are anchored on the unified UOR substrate (the deferred σ-axis convergence, ADR-026/holospaces CC-51) — not a locally-served image but a set of objects on the shared content-addressed network. Every object — every entry in the OS-wide κ-route closure AND every entry in every app's lock closure — is DUAL-AXIS: it carries its OS serving key (did:holo:sha256) AND its unified-substrate σ-axis κ (a did:holo:blake3 alsoKnownAs alias = BLAKE3 over the canonical form, byte-identical to hologram's kappa()). The κ-route resolves any object by EITHER axis at /.holo/<axis>/<hex>, re-derived and refused on mismatch (Law L5) — dev (holo-serve-fhs) and prod (the content-verify Service Worker holo-fhs-sw.js) identically (Law L2). So an OS or app object resolves on any substrate peer by its content address. BLAKE3≡kappa() is grounded in the external σ-axis KAT oracle (holo-blake3 row, never self-reference); the few apps with un-vendored binary bundles are reported, not silently passed.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Laws L1 (content not location) · L2 (one canonical rule, dev≡prod) · L4 (everything through the substrate) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) — docs/08-Concepts §Canonical forms and κ-labels · UOR-ADDR (κ-label = <axis>:<hex> = H(canonical_form)) · hologram's σ-axis BLAKE3 kappa() (the EXTERNAL κ-addressing oracle, KAT-proven via tools/holo-blake3-witness.mjs) · W3C DID Core (the did:holo:blake3 alsoKnownAs) · W3C Subresource Integrity + multibase",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-substrate-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Substrate"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#corpus-addressed",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "EVERY first-party file in Hologram OS2 + Hologram Apps is a first-class, attribute-addressed object native to the unified UOR substrate — not only the served runtime + app closures, but the WHOLE corpus (the OS image, the build/witness tools, the native host, the docs, every app). The substrate object index (os/etc/substrate-index.json) gives each file its DUAL-AXIS content address — did:holo:sha256 (OS serving) ⊕ did:holo:blake3 (the substrate σ-axis ≡ hologram's kappa()) — so identity is the content, never the path (Law L1), and every object re-derives (Law L5). Consume-by-reference (ADR-006): external/regenerable trees (.git · node_modules · Rust target · the holospaces substrate submodule, whose identity is upstream) are excluded, not re-minted; transient runtime artifacts (logs · progress · witness outputs) are not canonical forms and are not indexed. The index is deterministic (sorted, no timestamps) so it re-derives byte-for-byte. A concurrently-generating process (a live model-compile) is reported as drift, not hidden.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Laws L1 (content not location) · L3 (the store is the memory — the index is the address space) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) — docs/08-Concepts §Canonical forms and κ-labels · ADR-006 (consume by reference, never restate) · UOR-ADDR (κ-label = <axis>:<hex> = H(canonical_form)) · hologram's σ-axis BLAKE3 kappa() (the EXTERNAL κ-addressing oracle, KAT-proven via tools/holo-blake3-witness.mjs) · W3C DID Core · W3C SRI + multibase",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-corpus-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Substrate"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#serverless",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The SHIPPED Hologram OS is 100% serverless. Its surface is the sealed image (os-closure) + the content-verify Service Worker (holo-fhs-sw.js), served from a dumb static host: the worker is PURE content-routing + Law-L5 re-derivation (both κ axes, refuse-on-mismatch) and carries NO server, proxy, or backend logic. The optional companion backends (SoundCloud/yt-dlp streaming · develop-to-κ · the watch-together room relay · the MCP forwarder · the web proxy) live ONLY in the dev server (tools/holo-serve-fhs.mjs), which is a DEV TOOL — not pinned in the image, not referenced by the worker. So boot, run, resolve and verify need no server (the #boot row proves it boots in real Chromium with zero server fallbacks); the companions are dev-only conveniences a shipped feature degrades gracefully without.",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C Service Workers · WHATWG Fetch · holospaces Law L1 (no servers; no host/path/URL as identity) · L4 (everything through the substrate) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) — docs/02-Architecture-Constraints",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-serverless-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Substrate"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#self-heal",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Hologram OS heals itself, autonomously and by content (ADR-0076). A content address is a perfect lie-detector but not a healer — so detection (re-derive every byte, refuse a mismatch, Law L5) is extended with RECOVERY: a corrupted or missing κ-object is re-fetched origin-agnostically from wherever its bytes live (durable κ-store · peers · IPFS · origin, torrent-style) and served ONLY after it re-derives to the SAME address, so a wrong byte from any source is refused and nothing is laundered. A device that heals an object keeps it (seeds it); a proactive idle scrub re-verifies the closure and pre-heals latent corruption before anyone asks, with no user action. Every repair mints a verifiable PROV-O heal receipt (the heal IS witnessed). The supervisor also EVOLVES — verify → refocus → evolve: it learns per-κ flakiness from each sweep's own outcomes (the same repair/miss data the heal-log records) and re-sweeps the historically-unstable objects FIRST, and under a heal-budget more often, while confirming and leaving the stable ones alone; the learned ranking is inspectable (flakiness()) and folded into the health attestation, so 'the OS adapts' is a re-derivable fact, not a claim. The priority signal is REPAIRS (broke-and-recovered, worth re-watching); a MISS (currently unreachable) is tracked but never escalated, so an unresolvable κ cannot monopolise a small heal-budget and starve the objects that can be fixed — staleness rotates it through its fair share. The signal is plain integer history — no clock, no randomness — so the sweep stays deterministic and re-derivation-safe. The sealed ANCHOR — constitution, gate-pinned constants, OS-closure root — is NEVER auto-healed: a broken anchor stays fail-closed and is surfaced to the operator, never rewritten to match drifted bytes.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Laws L1/L3/L5 (identity is content · storage is a cache of the address space · verify by re-derivation) · ADR-026 Sovereign Delivery (cache → peers → origin, demoted) · W3C DID Core · W3C PROV-O · W3C Subresource Integrity · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · IPFS Trustless Gateways (a sha-256 κ IS a CIDv1 sha2-256)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-heal-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Substrate"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#open-web",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The healer reaches the WHOLE OPEN INTERNET, and proves itself in W3C linked data. The internet is a hypergraph of objects (nodes) addressed by their self-verifying attributes (κ); an HTTPS IRI, an IPFS CIDv1 (a sha-256 κ IS one), a holo:// alias and a did:holo are all EDGES to the same node. The recovery chain follows any edge — the device's durable κ-store, the origin, the object's own W3C DID Core alsoKnownAs HTTPS IRIs, content-address gateways, IPFS Trustless Gateways, and WebRTC-mesh peers — and admits a copy ONLY after it re-derives to the address (Law L5), so fetching from ANY server (a stranger's CDN, a mirror, a gateway) is safe: a wrong or hostile byte loses, the URL is merely a place a copy happens to live. Agents and humans get a first-class importObject(κ | https-URL) → resolve any node from any edge and re-derive it, or fetch an arbitrary web object and content-address it so it joins the substrate — the open web as one address space. And the self-healing artifacts are 100% standards-native: the heal receipt and the health attestation are valid JSON-LD (W3C DID Core + Data Integrity + PROV-O + schema.org @context), content-addressed and re-derivable, and every hosheal: term they mint is DEFINED in a published, dereferenceable OWL ontology (usr/share/ns/heal.jsonld) — mint-nothing, so the open semantic web (humans and agents) can interpret every heal.",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C DID Core (alsoKnownAs equivalence edges) · W3C Subresource Integrity + multiformats CID/multihash (κ ⇆ CIDv1 sha2-256) · WHATWG Fetch · IETF RFC 8615 (.well-known) · W3C JSON-LD 1.1 / Linked Data · W3C PROV-O · W3C RDF Schema / OWL 2 · IPFS Trustless Gateways · holospaces Laws L1/L2/L5",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-web-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Substrate"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#substrate-oracle",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Interop EXERCISED against the LIVE hologram substrate, not a reimplementation: the substrate's OWN compiled kappa() (the holospaces_web wasm — the real code peers run) independently derives the SAME σ-axis κ that Hologram OS minted and recorded for REAL objects (the canonical shell, the σ-axis primitive, the Files app, a just-sealed vendored bundle). So every OS/app object resolves + verifies on a real substrate peer by its content address (the declared did:holo:blake3 alias IS the substrate's live derivation). Offline (no wasm), the authority is the KAT-pinned holo-blake3 row.",
      "hosc:authority": "the hologram substrate's own kappa() (holospaces_web wasm, github.com/Hologram-Technologies/hologram — the EXTERNAL implementation oracle) · UOR-ADDR (κ-label = <axis>:<hex> = H(canonical_form)) · holospaces Law L1/L5 · the KAT-pinned holo-blake3 row (offline authority)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-substrate-oracle-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Substrate"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#atlas-coordinates",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Every UOR object has a deterministic, self-verifying COORDINATE in the finite Φ-Atlas-12288 torus (the sealed E8·ATLAS96 object, did:holo:sha256:f82435da…), derived PURELY from its content address (κ) — attribute-derived, re-derivable by anyone from the κ alone (Law L5), and always inside the finite space. The math is verbatim upstream (atlas-12288: Φ(p,b)=(p<<8)|b · R96=b%96 · ℤ₄₈×ℤ₂₅₆=12,288), cross-checked against the sealed object’s own resonator-geometry.js. The content→torus embedding is uniform (objects spread across cells, all 96 R96 classes used). Because the torus is FINITE per level and content-addressing is ACYCLIC, every object is BOTH a point in its parent’s atlas AND itself an atlas for its sub-objects — finite shapes, unbounded depth, no recursion. The canonical shell self-declares its own coordinate. This is an interpretable coordinate NAMESPACE over the object graph — NOT an isolation, storage, compute, or quantum layer (isolation = the W3C sandbox + Law-L5 verify + the conscience gate).",
      "hosc:authority": "UOR-Foundation/atlas-12288 (the verbatim Φ-Atlas-12288 invariants, vendored) · UOR-ADDR (κ-label = <axis>:<hex> = H(canonical_form)) · holospaces Law L1 (content not location) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) · the sealed E8·ATLAS96 object’s resonator-geometry.js (the canonical source)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-atlas-coord-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Substrate"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#kstore",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The store IS the memory (Law L3), operational in any browser. The content-addressed κ-store (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-kstore.js) resolves any object BY ITS κ through three tiers — an in-memory Map (sub-µs), OPFS (sub-ms, survives reload), then the κ-route /.holo/<axis>/<hex> over HTTP (cold) — VERIFIED by re-derivation on first fetch (Law L5; a wrong κ is refused, the origin demoted to one untrusted CDN). So the 2nd-and-later open of any object or app is the SUB-MILLISECOND in-memory rebind, not a re-fetch: measured in real Chromium a warm resolve is about 0.5 µs (over 50,000x a cold HTTP+verify), and re-opening a real app rebinds its whole κ-manifest from memory in about 0.2 ms. Each object's atlas coordinate is its content-derived placement (computed, not looked up). This turns a holospace's tiny κ-manifest into a running app by rebind.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Law L3 (the store is the memory) · L1 (content not location) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) · W3C File System Access / OPFS · WHATWG Fetch · W3C Web Cryptography (SHA-256) + the σ-axis BLAKE3 · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · real Chromium via Playwright",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-kstore-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#sw-cache",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The live app-open path is content-addressed and network-free on re-open. The shell mounts every app as an iframe that fetches its bytes BY PATH through the content-verify Service Worker (os/holo-fhs-sw.js) — a child iframe is a separate browsing context whose subresources the parent page's in-memory arena CANNOT serve, so the SW is the honest live-runtime delivery layer (network-free milliseconds, not the page-side sub-microsecond arena). The worker now VERIFIES app bytes too, not only OS bytes: on the first request under apps/<id>/ it lazily folds that app's own holospace.lock.json closure into its L5 index, so every app byte is re-derived to its pinned κ and a mismatch is refused (a wrong κ on the κ-route is 404 — not in the content index). Verified bytes are then stored in a CacheStorage keyed by κ (/.holo/<axis>/<hex>), so identical bytes are cached ONCE and shared across every app (dedup), and the 2nd-and-later open is served from cache with no origin fetch and no re-hash (x-holo-cache: hit). Measured in real Chromium: a cold open verifies + fills the cache, the warm re-open is network-free at about a quarter the time.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Laws L1 (content not location) · L3 (the store is the memory — extended to the SW's persistent CacheStorage) · L5 (verify by re-derivation; app bytes, not just OS bytes) · W3C Service Workers + Cache API · WHATWG Fetch · W3C Web Cryptography (SHA-256) + the σ-axis BLAKE3 · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · one shared flat→FHS mapping (lib/holo-fhs-map.mjs, dev server ≡ SW) · real Chromium via Playwright",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-sw-cache-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#runtime-adoption",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "EVERY hologram app takes advantage of the Holo Runtime, and EVERY app self-resolves from its content-derived κ address — so a holo app is shareable by ONE content link that runs fast in any browser. Two things are proven end-to-end. (1) STRUCTURAL, all 34 apps: every app collapses to a single content-derived ROOT κ (its whole self-describing identity — the thing a link carries), every entry in its closure is κ-pinned (no app byte is trusted by location), and a sampled leaf of every app RE-DERIVES to its pinned κ (the bytes hash to their address — Law L5), so each app self-resolves from content, not path. (2) LIVE, a representative sample (files · notepad · wallet · search · git · forge) driven in real Chromium: each is delivered through the ONE content-verify Holo Runtime Service Worker with no per-app opt-in (the gateway registers it at root scope, so every nested app inherits it); each app's first open verifies + fills the κ-cache and its SECOND open is NETWORK-FREE from the κ-keyed content cache (x-holo-cache: hit — the ultra-low-latency advantage); each app's index SELF-RESOLVES on the κ-route (the bytes returned for its κ match), and a wrong κ is refused. No app was modified to gain this — adoption is universal and automatic because delivery and addressing are the runtime's, not each app's.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Laws L1 (content not location) · L3 (the store is the memory — the κ-keyed cache) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) — every app re-derives to its κ · the three-tier model (shell · runtime · apps, os/lib/holo-runtime.mjs) · W3C Service Workers + Cache API · WHATWG Fetch · W3C Web Cryptography (SHA-256) · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · rests on #runtime, #kstore, #sw-cache · real Chromium via Playwright over all 34 app locks + a 6-app live sample",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-runtime-adoption-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#share-runtime",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "An existing holo app is shareable by ONE content link that always opens and runs on the ultra-low-latency Holo Runtime — proven literally, the Telegram path. The share link the shell emits (holospace.html?app=<ref>#k=<κ>, the Share-to-Run convention, ADR-064) is opened in a COLD, fresh browser context — no cache, no service worker, no prior visit, exactly what happens when someone taps a link from a chat app on a device that has never seen the origin. It must, and does: (1) OPEN and RENDER the app fullscreen with the Share-to-Run chrome (the app actually paints in its sandboxed frame — measured cold in real Chromium in a few hundred ms); (2) SELF-RESOLVE the app by its content address (the app's bytes return from the κ-route and match its κ); (3) run on the ONE Holo Runtime delivery worker (holo-fhs-sw.js — the κ-keyed content cache + app-byte L5 verification), the SAME runtime as the rest of the OS — the share path was unified onto it (it no longer uses a separate per-app worker), so a shared app is content-verified and the runtime's, not bare HTTP; (4) the SECOND open is NETWORK-FREE from the κ-cache (x-holo-cache: hit). One link, any browser, no install, no account, no server — opens fast, runs verified, re-opens network-free.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Laws L1 (content not location — the link IS the κ) · L2 (one canonical delivery wire — the share path registers the SAME holo-fhs-sw.js runtime worker, not a separate per-app SW) · L4 (everything through the substrate) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) · Share-to-Run (ADR-064) · W3C Service Workers + Cache API · W3C iframe sandbox (the app's isolated realm) · WHATWG Fetch · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · rests on #runtime, #sw-cache, #share-to-run · real Chromium via Playwright, cold fresh context (the Telegram tap), with a screenshot of the running shared app as proof",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-share-link-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#pretty-link",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "An external share address can be SHORT, ATTRACTIVE and self-verifying at once — without breaking decentralized interoperability. The principle: the name is a hint, the κ is the truth. (1) SHORTER + standard: a κ (did:holo:sha256:<64 hex>, 80 chars) is spelled as a CIDv1 (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-cid.mjs — multibase base32 · multicodec raw · sha2-256, ~59 chars, bafkrei…), the exact same digest in the envelope the whole content-addressing ecosystem speaks (IPFS · IPLD), so it is shorter AND more interoperable; it round-trips losslessly back to the identical κ (proven for every sampled app). (2) CLEANER: a /~<app>#k=<cid> route replaces holospace.html?app=…#k=did:holo:… — the path is a human hint, the #k= CID is the content handle. (3) PRETTIER: the route serves a per-app Open Graph card a chat crawler reads from static HTML (og:title · og:image · summary_large_image), and the og:image is a DETERMINISTIC, content-derived κ-identicon (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-identicon.mjs — the colour and glyph come straight from the digest, so the picture re-derives exactly like the address; same κ → same picture, distinct per app). INTEROP PRESERVED: nothing is resolved without the κ re-deriving — the CID losslessly carries the content address, the served app bytes are re-derived by the runtime worker (Law L5), and any shortener/name resolver is untrusted-by-construction (a lie is refused). Proven live in a cold browser: the clean CID link opens + renders the app on the Holo Runtime worker, and the CID decodes to the app's real κ. (Honest boundary: the dev server injects per-app OG meta to prove the mechanism; a static host needs the build to pre-render per-app /~<app> pages, or host templating — the CID, the clean route, and a generic card work on any host.)",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Law L1 (content not location — the link carries the κ as a CID) · L2 (one canonical mapping) · L5 (verify by re-derivation — the CID round-trips, the identicon re-derives, the bytes re-derive) · IPFS/IPLD multiformats (CIDv1 · multibase · multicodec · multihash) — the interoperability bridge · W3C did:holo (the κ) · Open Graph protocol + Twitter Cards (the chat preview) · real Chromium via Playwright, cold context, with a rendered card",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-pretty-link-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#runtime",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The Holo Runtime is the SINGLE canonical native runtime for every hologram app (os/lib/holo-runtime.mjs). It is the second of the three tiers — holospace shell (the OS frame) · Holo Runtime (the core every app inherits) · the apps themselves — and it lives exactly once at os/usr/lib/holo, reached by every app through the flat /_shared/ URL space that the ONE flat→FHS map (lib/holo-fhs-map.mjs) routes there. No engine is duplicated between the runtime and any app bundle (an app's own _shared/ may carry only app-only engines with no runtime master). Beyond 'shared engines live here once', the runtime DECLARES the substrate capabilities every app inherits as one definition: the content-addressed STORE (holo-kstore.js — resolve any object by its κ through a contiguous in-memory arena that earns L1/L2 residency by locality → OPFS → the κ-route, verified by re-derivation, Law L5); the content-verify DELIVERY wire (holo-fhs-sw.js — re-derives every byte, OS and app alike by folding each app's own lock into its L5 index, refuses a wrong κ, and serves verified bytes from a κ-keyed CacheStorage so the 2nd open is network-free and deduped across apps; registered at root scope by the gateway so every nested app inherits it with no per-app wiring — the honest live-runtime re-open path, since a child iframe is a separate context the page-side arena cannot serve); and the content-derived ADDRESSING axes (the σ-axis BLAKE3 ≡ the upstream kappa(), and the finite Φ-Atlas-12288 coordinate). Each capability lives once and is BOUND by apps, never reimplemented (Law L2), and its behavioral guarantees rest on the proven #kstore and #sw-cache rows.",
      "hosc:authority": "holospaces Laws L1 (content not location) · L2 (one canonical form, no drift) · L3 (the store is the memory) · L4 (everything through the substrate) · L5 (verify by re-derivation) · the three-tier model (shell · runtime · apps) declared in os/lib/holo-runtime.mjs · one shared flat→FHS mapping (lib/holo-fhs-map.mjs) · rests on the proven #kstore (the store) + #sw-cache (the delivery wire) + #atlas-coordinates (addressing) rows",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-runtime-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
