      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#app-governed",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "EVERY holospace is GOVERNED at the host by Holo Terms + Holo Privacy — the two core consent functions, enforced where apps mount, not left to each app to opt into. Holo Terms (MyTerms / IEEE 7012-2025) is the capability gate: the host clamps an app to declared ∩ the user's standing term + signed agreement before mounting (holo-launch.mount → the iframe sandbox). Holo Privacy (W3C VC/DPV selective disclosure) is the disclosure gate: the host owns the wallet/keys, an app frame holds nothing, and any disclosure is brokered by the host (holo-gov.js) which stamps the recipient from what it actually mounted (un-forgeable) and gates under the user's stance — default-deny. Both are SURFACED as one shield per focused app (Terms · Privacy), so enforcement is visible, never silent. Universal by construction: proven at the host frames (shell.html · holospace.html), so no app can be an ungoverned island",
      "hosc:authority": "IEEE 7012-2025 (MyTerms) · W3C Verifiable Credentials + DPV (selective disclosure, eddsa-jcs-2022) · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS, content-address re-derivation, Law L5) · holo-launch.mount (the capability sandbox chokepoint) · static analysis of the canonical host frames + the governance module",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-app-governed-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#app-ui-tokens",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo UI conformance extends from text size to COLOR + SHAPE (ADR-0057) — the canonical palette (--holo-bg/-surface/-ink/-accent/…) and radius (--holo-radius-sm/-/-lg) tokens are the single source, and a hardcoded hex color or px border-radius in an app's authored shell bypasses them. Because color is IDENTITY (apps + the faithful reproductions keep their own colors under the ADOPT-vs-OWN model, ADR-0023), this is a no-regression RATCHET, not a forced rewrite: an app may not add hardcoded themeable values beyond its committed baseline, so the corpus can only get MORE token-conformant. Radius exact-matches (8/12/16px) are adopted as tokens pixel-for-pixel (burndown-app-radius.mjs)",
      "hosc:authority": "ADR-0030 (Holo UI) · ADR-0023 (the --holo-* token contract + adopt-vs-own) · ADR-0057 (the readability floor) · the 'betterer' no-new-violations ratchet · static analysis of the served app repo",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-app-token-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-desk",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Desk is the substrate-native DESKTOP (ADR-0061) — the full native folder/icon experience in any browser, made magical by leaning into the UOR content-addressed substrate. CREATE: right-click 'New ▸ Folder/Text/App shortcut' (+ inline-rename; Home is read/WRITE). PIN ANYTHING: drop or paste any app, file, URL, or κ/did:holo onto the desktop and it becomes a self-verifying icon (files import + content-address on write; identifiers become object pins; apps become launchers). ORGANISE: drag to arrange, NEST onto a folder, marquee multi-select, copy/cut/paste, keyboard nav + type-ahead, and delete → Trash with Undo (⌘Z). PROVE: every icon carries its did:holo κ (a verify badge re-derives on hover, Law L5), 'Copy holo:// link' shares an object by content address, 'Copy desktop κ' turns the WHOLE arrangement into one shareable address, and Quick Look (Space) shows the live κ. FEEL: reskins to the host OS (Windows/macOS) via HoloPlatform, insets around the dock, animates with taste (reduced-motion aware); folders show covers that match their contents. Reuses the OS engines, no foreign runtime (ADR-0029); proven by driving the real desktop in Chromium (23 checks).",
      "hosc:authority": "ADR-0061 (Holo Desk) · ADR-0058 (Holo Files VFS) · ADR-0032 (Holo Icons) · ADR-0030/0057 (Holo UI) · ADR-0029 (adopt-don’t-run) · W3C OPFS / File System Access · Web Crypto · driving the real desktop in Chromium",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-desk-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-ux",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo UX is the single canonical, self-verifying source of the EXPERIENCE (ADR-0062) — the experience analogue of Holo UI's token contract. The system autodetects the host OS (Windows · macOS · iOS · iPadOS · Android · ChromeOS · Linux) and adapts its native feel dynamically — modifier key, window-control side, font, accent, shortcuts (holo-platform.js → data-holo-platform, seeded without overriding the user) — so it feels familiar and effortless on every machine. Thirteen tenets (the five founding principles + Steve Jobs's eight UX lessons) are each a checkable obligation; capability tier, plain voice and a tier-aware resource budget (time · attention · compute · memory · energy held sacred, interaction ≤100ms / RAIL) are resolved, not guessed. The canonical parameters are sealed as ONE UOR object (etc/holo-ux/doctrine.uor.json) that re-derives to its content address and whose source links re-derive (Law L5) — every holospace binds the κ rather than re-implementing UX",
      "hosc:authority": "ADR-0062 (Holo UX doctrine) · ADR-0030 (Holo UI) · ADR-0028 (Holo UX Profile) · W3C UA Client Hints (host autodetect) · WCAG 2.2 (readability · target size · animation) · RAIL / W3C Web Performance · W3C OWL 2 / RDFS / SKOS (the hosux: vocabulary) · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · verify by re-derivation (Law L5)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-ux-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#app-ux-conformance",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The Holo UX doctrine (ADR-0062) is strictly adhered to by EVERY holospace application, not just the OS chrome — so every app is beautiful, functional and coherent with the whole OS. Loading the ONE engine every app already loads (holo-theme.js) bootstraps the Holo UX runtime (holo-ux.js), so every app inherits the WHOLE doctrine — the host-OS native feel, the capability tier, the resource budget, the live propagation — by binding one canonical wire (Law L2), with no per-app script tag. This witness proves that inheritance is real for every served app (the carrier is intact + the canonical doctrine object re-derives + every app loads the engine), and holds each app to its OWN-shell obligations: its manifest keeps the plain voice (jargon-free — signal over noise); it honors prefers-reduced-motion through the ONE OS-wide guard every app inherits from holo-theme.css (time/compute/energy held sacred — WCAG 2.3.3, no per-app copy needed, no app may override it with its own !important motion); and its modifier keys are NATIVE-ADAPTIVE — no unconditional Apple-only glyph (⌘/⌥), the host's modifier is derived (HoloPlatform/metaKey) or rendered by the inherited data-holo-shortcut helper (⌘N on macOS · Ctrl+N on Windows/Linux). Read-only over the served app repo — no edits, no re-lock",
      "hosc:authority": "ADR-0062 (Holo UX doctrine) · ADR-0030/0057 (Holo UI) · WCAG 2.2 (2.3.3 Animation from Interactions · 1.4.x readability) · the plain voice register (holo-voice.mjs) · RAIL / W3C Web Performance · the 'betterer' no-new-violations ratchet · static analysis of the served app repo",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-app-ux-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#share-to-run",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Share-to-Run — the growth loop (ADR-064): a SHARED holospace link (one carrying #k= provenance) lands a GUEST fullscreen in the running app, with an OS-level chrome laid OVER the app's sandboxed frame (so the substrate speaks, not the app) — run it, REMIX it (one tap to your own editable copy in the World shell), SHARE it (the content-addressed link, no sign-in), SAVE it (the pull to create your self-sovereign Space, never a gate before value). The chrome shows the app's VERIFIED content address (κ, re-derived not URL-trusted), is contextual to shared landings only (a bare kiosk link stays clean), rides the canonical --holo-* tokens + the readability floor, and honors prefers-reduced-motion. The native, private-first viral loop (share-to-run-to-remix) over the content-addressed substrate — no central feed, no parallel infrastructure (Law L1/L4). The loop SELF-seeds from EVERY creation surface: both the World shell's Share (its modal · QR · Copy all carry it) AND the in-app Manage panel emit this magic link, so a creator's first share lands the recipient in the chrome (the frame resolves the link by content address OR by the app's served-path id). Proven by driving the whole loop in real Chromium (13 checks — shared landing renders, kiosk stays clean, the World shell Share AND the Manage panel each emit the magic link, a path-built link resolves and lands in the chrome, and that link lands the next guest back in the chrome: the loop closed end-to-end)",
      "hosc:authority": "ADR-064 (Holo Share-to-Run) · W3C Web Share API · holospaces Law L1 (identity is content) / L4 (no parallel infrastructure) / L5 (re-derivation) · ADR-053 (Title — remix lineage + publish/own) · ADR-0057/0062 (Holo UI/UX conformance floors) · ADR-027 (signaling-free mesh — presence) · ADR-0043 (Atlas — opt-in public feed) · real-Chromium render proof",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-share-to-run-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-product",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Product is the canonical upstream foundation for building beautiful, valuable and delightful Hologram-native products (ADR-0065) — it BUNDLES and BALANCES the two already-wired faculties of the UX·&·UI diagram into one self-verifying object: five UX faculties (interaction design · wireframes · information architecture · user research · scenarios — the experience, Holo UX) and five UI faculties (visual design · colours · graphic design · layouts · typography — the look, Holo UI), each mapped to where it is already wired in the OS and each a checkable obligation, with neither hemisphere allowed to ship without the other. It also binds a HYBRID delivery method (discover · define · design · build · verify · deliver/iterate) drawn from the field's project-management frameworks (Agile · Scrum · Kanban · Waterfall · Lean · PRINCE2 · Six Sigma) — the predictive-governance-plus-agile-execution the substrate already lives (an ADR is the decision record, a witness is the definition of done, the fail-closed gate is the stage-gate, the resource budget is the Lean waste discipline, a sealed κ is the predictable artifact). The bundle is sealed as ONE UOR object (etc/holo-product/product.uor.json) that re-derives to its content address and Merkle-links BOTH hemispheres — the sealed Holo UX doctrine and the canonical Holo UI token/engine layer — so a product binds the κ rather than re-deciding the basics (Law L5); it rests on the proven Holo UI + Holo UX gate rows",
      "hosc:authority": "ADR-0065 (Holo Product) · ADR-0030/0057 (Holo UI) · ADR-0062 (Holo UX) · project-management frameworks (Agile · Scrum · Kanban · Waterfall · Lean · PRINCE2 · Six Sigma · Hybrid, cited not minted) · W3C OWL 2 / RDFS / SKOS (the hosprod: vocabulary) · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · verify by re-derivation (Law L5)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-product-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-pm",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Product Manager is the canonical full-cycle product-management framework for Hologram-native products + applications (ADR-0066) — the bridge that turns ideas into scalable, enterprise-grade products that solve real pain points. It STRICTLY adopts the Pragmatic Framework (pragmaticinstitute.com/product/framework) VERBATIM — 37 activities ('boxes') in 7 categories (Market · Focus · Business · Planning · Programs · Enablement · Support), on the strategic→tactical axis, a clear path from a great idea to a great product — and WIRES every activity Hologram realizes to the tool that executes it (User Personas → Holo UX capability tiers · Use Scenarios/Stakeholder Comm → the plain voice · Requirements/Roadmap/Positioning → Holo Product · Buyer Experience → Holo UX · Launch/Awareness/Advocacy → Holo Share-to-Run · Pricing/Revenue/Profitability → Holo Own·Settle · Buy-Build-Partner/Innovation → Holo App build·compose · Measurement → the witnessed gate · Operations → the conscience gate · Content/Sales Tools → the Holo SDK + scaffolder), so the framework is EXECUTED on the substrate, not just described; the market/business judgment boxes stay the PM's job (NIHITO — no tool can own them). It is sealed as ONE self-verifying UOR object (etc/holo-pm/pm.uor.json) that re-derives to its content address and Merkle-links the Holo Product foundation it manages + every wired tool (Law L5); it is surfaced as the canonical PANE (holo-pm.html) and exposed through the Holo SDK (pm()), to deliver one seamless, unified, coordinated PM framework",
      "hosc:authority": "ADR-0066 (Holo Product Manager) · the Pragmatic Framework (pragmaticinstitute.com/product/framework, cited verbatim — 37 boxes / 7 categories) · ADR-0065 (Holo Product) · ADR-0062/0030/0057 (Holo UX/UI) · ADR-0064 (Holo Share-to-Run) · ADR-0053 (Holo Own/Settle) · ADR-0050 (Holo SDK) · W3C OWL 2 / RDFS / SKOS (the hospm: vocabulary) · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · verify by re-derivation (Law L5)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-pm-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Display manager & UI"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#atlas96-resonator",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The Atlas 96 Resonator is the Φ-Atlas-12288 boundary made PHYSICAL, AUDIBLE and PROVABLE — the whole 12,288-cell torus (T² = ℤ₄₈ × ℤ₂₅₆, verbatim upstream invariants: R96 = b % 96 · Φ(p,b) = (p << 8) | b) as an interactive fiber instrument: pull a cell, field-grab the whole structure, squeeze it until it buckles, pluck it; morph the SAME cells through 1D cycle → 2D sheet → 3D torus → 4D Clifford torus in S³; hear deformation as 96-EDO partials over the R96 classes (class c sounds at 220·2^(c/96) Hz) with truth ≙ conservation (the strain budget returns to 0). Its structure is NOT parametric — every irregular artifact of the weave (each fiber kink, each hole) is a byte of DNA(p,b) = SHA-256(atlasObjectId ‖ Φ(p,b)), zero free parameters, zero RNG, sealed in a PROV-O receipt and re-derived LIVE in the tab (Law L5); tampering ONE codepoint of the atlas object is refused with all 12,288 cells re-deriving differently. It is 100% BROWSER-NATIVE and HARDWARE-MAXIMAL: the atlas engine itself (R96 · Φ · truth) is COMPILED IN THE TAB by Holo Forge from the verbatim upstream C and verified against its sealed build receipt — five live re-derivations in total; the structure is derived once, content-addressed, and REBOUND O(1) by κ on every later visit (with a full background re-derivation, so O(1) never weakens the proof); the physics lives on the user's GPU — a WebGPU compute tier (Jacobi PBD over all cells and constraints in WGSL, storage-buffer instanced fibers, zero per-frame CPU geometry) with the WebGL2 tier as the verified fallback — and the renderer adapts to the hardware's real headroom up to an 8K-class backbuffer. This is the decidable answer to 'how do we know the model didn't just classify the shape and apply the math formula — did the mesh capture the specific, irregular artifacts?': re-derive, or be refused",
      "hosc:authority": "UOR-Foundation/atlas-12288 @ aef42a6 (verbatim, MIT — the 48×256→96 Prime Structure, vendored not re-implemented) · W3C PROV-O (the structure + build receipts) · DID-Core + RFC 8785 JCS (did:holo self-verification) · FIPS 180-4 SHA-256 (the per-cell derivation) · Holo Forge ADR-0051 (the in-tab κ-transform) · W3C WebGPU + WGSL · WebGL2 + Web Audio · OPFS (the κ-keyed O(1) rebind) · Law L5: verify by re-derivation, tamper → refuse",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/atlas96-resonator-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Holospaces"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-q-spine",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Q is a substrate-native chat app (LibreChat-parity spine, reimplemented natively): conversations persist as content-addressed κ-objects — NOT a database — the parentMessageId branch tree is a verify-on-load Merkle-DAG (every message links its parent's κ; regenerate/edit = a new sibling κ; fork = a new conversation referencing the SAME κ-objects, O(1), zero copy), and every answer is a re-derivable PROV-O inference receipt sealed to its own did:holo. Tampering one byte of any message or receipt is refused by re-derivation; identical (context ⊕ prompt ⊕ model ⊕ params) replays from the κ-memo in O(1) with no decode",
      "hosc:authority": "IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · W3C PROV-O · W3C DID Core · W3C Subresource Integrity · UOR content-addressing (κ = H(canonical form)) · verify-by-re-derivation (Law L1/L3/L5) · LibreChat data model (conversation/message/preset field names, reproduced not vendored)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/q-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Holospaces"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-code",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Code is a substrate-native, sovereign reproduction of the Claude Code terminal agent (apps/code) — the same faithful agentic experience (streaming replies, tool-call blocks, slash commands, plan mode, permission prompts, a content-addressed file/diff viewer), but the brain runs on YOUR machine and nothing is taken on trust. Its whole closure RE-DERIVES to its content address (a single did:holo, Law L5) and is self-contained over the OS runtime (0 fallbacks). The inference brain is a PLUGGABLE provider: a local, deterministic agent turns a request into REAL substrate tool calls (read · write · edit · glob · grep · verify · build · run · share over the holo-files content-addressed VFS, each result carrying the did:holo κ of the bytes it touched) with zero model download — OR the Holo Q (QVAC WebGPU, ADR-0052) on-device LLM, which runs the full desktop-Claude agentic loop: armed with the tool schemas + a coding persona, the model reasons and emits Qwen2.5 function-calls, and the agent executes each tool conscience-gated over the substrate and feeds the result back until it answers (composing Holo Q's own loader→engine + toolSystemPrompt/parseToolCalls wire-format; greedy decode is deterministic, so the turn re-derives — Law L5). Permission is the FAIL-CLOSED conscience gate (ADR-033): the agent evaluates every tool call against the OS Constitution and refuses when unsealed, with the familiar Claude Code modes (default · plan · auto · acceptEdits · bypass) layered on that constitutional floor. Every session seals to a re-derivable PROV-O work receipt (steps · target κ · conscience verdict) — a session you can prove, not just remember. The witness re-derives the shipped bytes AND executes the shipped provider logic (no browser, no server): the local brain demonstrably turns 'read src/greet.js' into a read_file tool call",
      "hosc:authority": "IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · W3C PROV-O · W3C DID Core · W3C Subresource Integrity · UOR content-addressing (κ = H(canonical form)) · verify-by-re-derivation (Law L1/L3/L5) · the OS Constitution conscience gate (ADR-033) · Anthropic Claude Code (terminal-agent UX, reproduced not vendored)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-code-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Holospaces"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#qvac-sdk",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The QVAC SDK (docs.qvac.tether.io) is encoded NATIVE to Hologram OS (ADR-0067) — Tether's local AI SDK as one self-verifying contract on the substrate, so a builder writes QVAC code and it just runs: beautiful, fast, lean, serverless. It encodes the WHOLE QVAC surface — the 13 AI capabilities (text generation · embeddings · RAG · translation · classification · multimodal · image · video · transcription · text-to-speech · voice assistant · VLA · OCR · fine-tuning), the model lifecycle (a model is a content-addressed κ-disk, so loading verifies it), the runtime (cancel · suspend · resume · state · logging · profiler), P2P delegation and the OpenAI-compatible server — and SATISFIES it on the substrate: every capability call passes the fail-closed conscience gate (ADR-033), runs over the browser-native engine (a deterministic reference brain that ALWAYS runs with no download now; Holo Q / QVAC WebGPU, ADR-0052, when a model is bound), and seals a re-derivable PROV-O inference receipt — so local inference is PROVABLE, not just asserted (identical inputs replay the same κ; a tampered output is refused). The witness RUNS the shipped runtime façade in Node (a real completion streams tokens and its receipt re-derives; embeddings/RAG/classify are deterministic). Serverless: the OpenAI /v1 routes are answered by a Service-Worker fetch handler, no process, no port (Law L1/L4). Operative: the Holo SDK exposes qvac() and the scaffolder builds QVAC apps on the contract (builtOn qvac-sdk + @hologram/qvac + conformsTo the ns), so any builder ships an on-device AI holospace in one command. Encoded — not vendored — under the holospaces Laws; honest where weights are absent (the call reports the missing model, never fakes output)",
      "hosc:authority": "QVAC SDK (docs.qvac.tether.io, Apache-2.0 — encoded not vendored) · holospaces Laws L1 (identity is content) / L2 (one canonical rule, dev≡prod) / L4 (no parallel infrastructure) / L5 (verify by re-derivation) (github.com/Hologram-Technologies/holospaces) · ADR-033 (the conscience gate) · ADR-0052 (Holo Q / QVAC WebGPU) · ADR-0050 (Holo SDK) · OpenAI Chat Completions API (the /v1 surface, reproduced) · W3C PROV-O · W3C DID Core · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · W3C OWL 2 / RDFS / SKOS · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · verify by re-derivation (Law L5)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/qvac-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "AI & inference"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-bittensor",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "The live decentralized intelligence market (Bittensor / Subtensor) is projected INTO the substrate's agent fabric as self-verifying UOR objects, NOT bridged as a foreign runtime (ADR-0071) — because a Bittensor subnet IS already a NANDA registry (hotkey → neuron → axon → subnet task = AgentName → record → AgentFacts → endpoint → capability), the projection generalizes Holo NANDA (ADR-034) and is BETTER than a bridge: it re-derives. The metagraph at a block is a κ-rooted dcat:Catalog of neuron AgentFacts whose root did:holo PINS the block hash (so it re-derives against Bittensor's own Merkle chain, Law L5); each neuron is ONE document that is, on the same bytes, a valid NANDA AgentFacts record · a self-verifying UOR object · a W3C VC signed by the neuron's hotkey (dual trust — a vanilla NANDA resolver accepts the signature today, a UOR peer re-derives the address forever), and a did:pkh chain principal in the one κ graph (composing the Chain Abstraction Layer, #chain); tampering ANY byte breaks BOTH the content address and the hotkey signature. Yuma stake/consensus projects into a re-derivable AgentTrust attestation whose auditTrail IS the snapshot κ — a Sybil-resistant, capital-backed reputation oracle the substrate cannot mint, un-gameable because the witness recomputes it. κ ⇆ IPFS CIDv1 (the os-peers law) · the projection is deterministic (build-twice-equal) · mints nothing beyond the published bt: vocabulary. HONEST SCOPE: the Python bt SDK is not run — the chain read is an INGEST BOUNDARY (Subtensor's public, decentralized JSON-RPC, never a server we run; the witness uses a deterministic snapshot fixture); a stochastic inference is receipt-verifiable, not reproducible (the receipt binds, Holo Q ADR-0052); the dual-trust proof is modelled with deterministic Ed25519, standing in for the chain's real sr25519 hotkey signature",
      "hosc:authority": "Bittensor SDK (docs.learnbittensor.org/sdk/bt-api-ref) · Subtensor JSON-RPC · Yuma consensus · ss58 · Project NANDA AgentFacts + Index (arXiv:2507.14263, github.com/projnanda) · W3C DID Core + VC Data Integrity (eddsa-jcs-2022) + PROV-O + DCAT 3 + schema.org + EARL · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · IPLD/multiformats CIDv1 (κ⇄CIDv1, the os-peers law) · ADR-034 (Holo NANDA) · ADR-039 (Holo AgentTrust) · ADR-0052 (Holo Q) · holospaces Laws L1 (content not location) / L2 (canonical forms only) / L4 (everything through the substrate) / L5 (verify by re-derivation)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-bittensor-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "AI & inference"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-bittensor-mcp",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Bittensor (ADR-0071) is usable by AI agents over MCP — bittensor_snapshot · bittensor_agentfacts · bittensor_infer · bittensor_settle are advertised, JSON-Schema'd tools on the canonical Hologram MCP server (tools/list + /.well-known/mcp.json), each returning a SELF-VERIFYING UOR object the agent re-derives (Law L5): an agent maps a subnet's metagraph (a κ-rooted dcat:Catalog pinning the block hash), reads a neuron's dual-trust AgentFacts (NANDA record ⊕ UOR object ⊕ hotkey-signed VC), queries a miner and re-derives the PROV-O inference receipt, and settles TAO against PROVEN work (testnet-gated, tampered work pays nothing) — without trusting any server, and a tampered object is refused through the agent's own verify_object tool. The supply side of the agent economy, agent-callable.",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C Model Context Protocol (2024-11-05) · Bittensor SDK (docs.learnbittensor.org/sdk/bt-api-ref) · Project NANDA AgentFacts · W3C DID Core + VC Data Integrity (eddsa-jcs-2022) + PROV-O + DCAT 3 + schema.org · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical_form)) · ADR-0071 (Holo Bittensor) · verify by re-derivation (Law L5)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-bittensor-mcp-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "AI & inference"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-mind",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Mind PHASE 0 (ADR-0081) — agency is an OS-wide ambient κ-transform, not a single app. The re-derivable core (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-mind.mjs) composes ONE verb surface from the three agent doors that already exist (MCP ADR-0047 · agents ADR-0049 · skills ADR-0035), de-duped and capped; runs the intent → plan → act → seal loop where every step passes the EXISTING fail-closed conscience (ADR-033) before dispatch (a blocked step seals nothing, dispatches nothing — self-discipline as a structural property); and seals each action as a self-verifying PROV-O work receipt (ADR-045 shape) that re-derives byte-for-byte (Law L5) — a human action and an agent action through the IDENTICAL surface sealing the IDENTICAL shape. Identical asks replay O(1) (Law L3); no new store, transport, or trust root (Law L4). Witnessed 8/8 (the loop core is a pure function of injected plan/gate/dispatch, the holo-suspend pattern; the eighth check proves the isomorphic sealer is BYTE-IDENTICAL to the canonical Node envelope). SHELL-WIRED + gate-enforced: os/usr/share/frame/shell.html imports os/usr/lib/holo/holo-mind-ui.js, exposing window.HoloMind whose loop draws its roster from the LIVE doors (window.HoloMCP.descriptor ⊕ /.well-known/skills/index.json), gates every step through window.HoloConscience.evaluate (fail-closed until the constitution self-verifies), and dispatches through window.HoloMCP (the serverless in-page MCP transport) — and this row is required + in gate.mjs LIVE. Pending: the os-closure.json κ-pin for the two new served modules (offline precache + dual-axis anchor — the re-lock cascade, the same build step ADR-0052 defers for Holo Q; until then the SW falls back to network for them, never 409s), and the LEARNING κ-transform (the trace corpus + governed self-evolution, Phase 2). See docs/specs/holo-mind-implementation.md.",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C PROV-O · W3C DID Core · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · W3C Subresource Integrity · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical form)) · the Holo Constitution conscience gate (ADR-033) · ADR-0047/0049/0035 (the three agent doors) · ADR-045 (the work-receipt shape) · holospaces Laws L1/L3/L4/L5 (identity is content · the store is the memory · everything through the substrate · verify by re-derivation)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-mind-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-mind-evolve",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Mind PHASE 2 (ADR-0081) — the LEARNING κ-transform: κ(trace-corpus) ⊕ κ(optimizer) → κ(improved-skill), the skill writeback ADR-0035 deferred (\"a deterministic projection, not a mutable store\"), now GOVERNED and re-derivable. The trace corpus (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-mind-evolve.mjs) is an append-only, content-addressed chain — rewriting any PAST trace changes its κ and breaks every successor (Law L5, the AgentTrust hash-linked-chain idiom ADR-0039). A SkillRevision mints a NEW κ linking its parent (prov:wasRevisionOf) and what it derived from (prov:wasDerivedFrom the corpus head ⊕ the optimizer); it is IN FORCE only when EVERY governed condition holds — tests pass · within the size ceiling · conscience accepts · operator-ratified · cooling-off elapsed (mirrors the constitution's own governed succession, ADR-033 rule 4) — and the in-force fact is itself RE-DERIVED from the sealed gate, so a forged inForce over a failing gate is refused; the parent κ is preserved forever (rollback = re-pin the parent). Built on the adaptive-immune-classifier pattern (ADR-033: a learned model as a PURE FUNCTION of a content-addressed corpus) generalized from defense to all competence; the loop's LEARN step appends a trace per run and window.HoloMind.evolve runs the optimizer through the registered model. HONEST BOUNDARY: the optimizer's PROPOSAL is a stochastic LLM generation, NOT reproducible (ADR-0052's non-verifiable mode) — L5 holds over the AUDIT TRAIL (which corpus, which gates, ratified by whom), not the search. Witnessed (tools/holo-mind-evolve-witness.mjs, 10/10). PROMOTED: the trace corpus + the learned skills are DURABLE (write-through to the OS's OWN κ-store — holo-store.js idbBackend over the existing 'holo'/'kappa' IndexedDB, no new infrastructure, Law L4 — hydrated at boot so learning accumulates across reloads and tabs, Law L3), and an in-force revision RE-PROJECTS into the live roster (its SKILL.md frontmatter becomes a roster entry that WINS de-dup, the ADR-0035 writeback) so an evolved skill ACTUALLY CHANGES BEHAVIOR — verified live in a real browser (the corpus head + the learned skill survive a fresh page load; the evolved skill leads the roster). Required + in gate.mjs LIVE.",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C PROV-O (prov:wasRevisionOf / wasDerivedFrom / wasInformedBy) · W3C DID Core · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · W3C Subresource Integrity · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical form)) · the Holo Constitution governed succession + conscience gate + adaptive-immune-classifier pattern (ADR-033) · ADR-0035 (the skill writeback) · ADR-0039 (append-only hash-linked chain) · holospaces Laws L1/L2/L3/L4/L5 (identity is content · canonical forms only · the store is the memory · everything through the substrate · verify by re-derivation)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-mind-evolve-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-mind-soul",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Mind PHASE 3 (ADR-0081) — the SOUL, one objective made operational. (1) INTRINSIC DRIVES (anima's digital_desire, os/usr/lib/holo/holo-mind-soul.mjs): homeostatic urges (epistemic hunger Hₑ, fitness Fₐ) that PROPOSE curiosity/self goals — a proposal is NEVER an act; it raises a holo:Intent that runs the ordinary loop where the fail-closed conscience (ADR-033) gates every step, so self-discipline is STRUCTURAL (no path from a drive to an effect can skip the gate). The drive state is integer-only (no clock/random) so a tick re-derives (Law L5, the holo-heal idiom). (2) The COHERENCE measure — the soul's utility (maximize SIGNAL over NOISE): DETERMINISTIC and re-derivable ON PURPOSE (signal = a re-derivable + novel effect; noise = the unverifiable or duplicate), so the objective CANNOT be Goodharted by a model self-grade; the five JUDGED output-court principles (Care · Fairness · Autonomy · Responsibility · Justice, ADR-033 judgeOutput) are the model-judged measure of a GOOD action, wired at the loop's VERIFY (stochastic — honest boundary). (3) Self-verifying USER + SELF models: a deepening PRIVATE-FIRST user model (adapts to + teaches the user) and a persistent self identity with a divergence score (anima's SelfModel); κ-objects, revisioned (prov:wasRevisionOf), DURABLE (the OS κ-store), NEVER published (Law L1 + Data Sovereignty / Holo Privacy). Witnessed tools/holo-mind-soul-witness.mjs (8/8, incl. the REAL output court blocking PII on the Dignity red line); wired live into holo-mind-ui.js (window.HoloMind.drives / proposeGoals / runProposals / updateUser / snapshotSelf / primeDirective); required + in gate.mjs LIVE.",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C PROV-O (prov:wasRevisionOf) · W3C DID Core · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical form)) · the Holo Constitution output court + conscience gate (ADR-033, the nine-principle judgeOutput — Care/Fairness/Autonomy/Responsibility/Justice) · anima digital_desire + self_reflection (the drives + self model, re-expressed substrate-native) · holospaces Laws L1/L2/L3/L4/L5 (identity is content · canonical forms only · the store is the memory · everything through the substrate · verify by re-derivation)",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-mind-soul-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    },
    {
      "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-mind-orchestrate",
      "@type": "hosc:ConformanceAssertion",
      "name": "Holo Mind PHASE 4 (ADR-0081) — orchestration at scale. PARALLEL SUB-AGENTS: a sub-agent is an ordinary conscience-gated Holo Mind loop run; orchestrate (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-mind-orchestrate.mjs + the binding) runs N CONCURRENTLY (Promise.all over runLoop — content-addressed seals can't collide; the corpus head is touched ONCE, after the barrier, no race) and composes ONE self-verifying PROV-O WORK RECEIPT over their receipts — the Holo Orchestrate idiom (ADR-0045): the root κ is proof of the WHOLE collaboration, verifyDeep re-runs every sub-receipt with no orchestrator to trust, and a TAMPERED sub-receipt breaks the root (Law L5). Each sub-agent's every step still passes the fail-closed conscience (ADR-033) — orchestration adds reach, never a gate bypass; scoped sub-authority rides the existing UCAN seam (ADR-0042). SCHEDULED TASKS: a holo:ScheduledTask is a re-derivable κ-object {utterance, everyMs}; an OPT-IN in-tab ticker (window.HoloMind.startScheduler) fires DUE tasks through the gated loop, the CLOCK read at the EDGE (Date.now in the ticker; dueTasks is PURE) so the core stays re-derivation-safe — honest scope: serverless + in-tab, tasks fire only while the tab is open (no background server, like cron / Claude Desktop). UCAN-SCOPED SUB-AGENT DELEGATION (ADR-0042, re-expressed substrate-native): each sub-agent acts under a holo:Delegation — a NARROWED, revocable capability (a scoped verb set ⊆ its granter's; the attenuation chain is content-addressed via prov:wasDerivedFrom, so ESCALATION is caught by re-derivation); orchestrate ATTENUATES each sub-agent's roster to its grant, and REVOKING a delegation (window.HoloMind.revoke) invalidates its whole SUBTREE → that sub-agent is refused; the work receipt commits to the delegation κ each sub acted under (who acted, under what authority — ADR-0045 ⊕ 0042). Honest scope: the full UCAN signature / principal-alignment proof engine is the agent stack's (own.verifyChain / verify_delegation, ADR-0049). Witnessed tools/holo-mind-orchestrate-witness.mjs (8/8: work composes + re-derives, a tamper breaks the root, the task re-derives, due-logic is pure, delegation attenuates + scopes the roster + revokes the subtree); wired live (window.HoloMind.orchestrate / schedule / startScheduler / delegate / revoke); required + in gate.mjs LIVE.",
      "hosc:authority": "W3C PROV-O (prov:wasInformedBy — the work DAG) · W3C DID Core · IETF RFC 8785 (JCS) · W3C Subresource Integrity · UOR-ADDR (κ = H(canonical form)) · Holo Orchestrate (ADR-0045, the verifiable multi-agent work receipt) · Holo Delegate (ADR-0042, UCAN-scoped sub-authority) · the Holo Constitution conscience gate (ADR-033) · holospaces Laws L1/L2/L3/L4/L5",
      "hosc:witness": "tools/holo-mind-orchestrate-witness.mjs",
      "hosc:required": true,
      "hosc:category": "Runtime"
    }
  ]
}
